---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const attacks = [
  { attack: "Forge a receipt from nothing", stop: "The signature must resolve to a registered Ed25519 key in the registry. No key, no provenance.", residual: "Residual: a stolen key — out of scope here, handled by rotation + revocation." },
  { attack: "Backdate a decision", stop: "Append-only log + chain position. A receipt can't be quietly inserted into the past.", residual: "Residual: timestamp accuracy depends on the TSA you bind." },
  { attack: "Only publish flattering decisions", stop: "The Coverage metric divides verifying receipts by declared scope volume — the denominator is public and spot-checked.", residual: "Residual: a wildly under-declared scope is itself a visible signal." },
  { attack: "Collude with the scorer", stop: "Scoring is reproducible from public artifacts — anyone can recompute it. No trust in the scorer required.", residual: "Residual: none cryptographic; the artifacts are the audit." },
  { attack: "Alter the payload after sealing", stop: "The content hash commitment self-invalidates. One changed byte fails verification.", residual: "Residual: none — this is the core property." },
  { attack: "Replay an old receipt", stop: "Unique ID + chain position make a replayed receipt detectable as out of place.", residual: "Residual: depends on consumers checking chain position." }
];

const harder = [
  { q: "Who decides what's 'official'?", a: "A governed registry and authorization process — never payment. We say so in plain text: payment never grants official status, and the registry is a pilot." },
  { q: "Isn't this just a fancy log?", a: "A log you control proves nothing to a second party. The difference is independent verification: anyone re-runs the math against a published key and gets the same answer." },
  { q: "What if the spec is wrong?", a: "The spec, fixtures and verifier cores are open. Independent verifier agreement across runtimes is the trust anchor — and the standing challenge pays you to break it." }
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Hard Questions"
  description="The objections a serious reviewer asks first — privacy, forgery, governance — answered honestly, with the threat model and residual risks in the open."
>
  <section class="section section--tight">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Hard questions</p>
      <h1>The objections we don't dodge.</h1>
      <p class="lede">Five questions a serious reviewer asks in the first meeting. Two could kill the idea if we
        got them wrong — so we answer those in full, then the three that are harder than they look.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section--tight" style="padding-top:0">
    <div class="container stack-lg">
      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Q1 · the one that kills the project if we get it wrong</p>
        <h2>"If every decision is public, you've just leaked everyone's private data."</h2>
        <p>The manifest never contains the decision. What's public is a <strong>commitment</strong> —
          cryptographic proof that a specific, unaltered decision was sealed at a specific time by a registered
          key. The decision itself is revealed only to a party with legal standing to see it, who then checks
          it against that commitment.</p>
        <div class="grid grid-3" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
          <div class="card"><h3>Commit, don't expose</h3><p class="muted">The manifest stores a salted hash of the payload — enough to prove integrity, useless for reconstructing the data.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h3>Reveal on legal basis</h3><p class="muted">A subject, regulator or court receives cleartext and verifies it hashes to the commitment.</p></div>
          <div class="card"><h3>Aggregate, not individual</h3><p class="muted">Outcome rates are published as windowed statistics. The public sees patterns; never a person.</p></div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Q2 · we publish the attack surface and pay you to break it</p>
        <h2>"What stops someone from faking the whole thing?"</h2>
        <p>A trust system that can't say how it fails isn't trustworthy. Here's the attack surface, and what
          stops each one.</p>
        <div class="grid grid-2" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
          {attacks.map((a) => (
            <article class="card card--accent">
              <h3 style="font-size:1.05rem">{a.attack}</h3>
              <p class="muted">{a.stop}</p>
              <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:var(--fs-micro)">{a.residual}</p>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="muted" style="margin-top:1rem; font-size:var(--fs-small)">Disclosure loop: report → triage →
          fix → disclose → credit. Good-faith research is never met with legal threats.</p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Q3–5 · the harder ones</p>
        <h2>Three that are harder than they look.</h2>
        <div class="grid grid-3" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
          {harder.map((h) => (
            <article class="card"><h3 style="font-size:1.05rem">{h.q}</h3><p class="muted">{h.a}</p></article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="section--ground" style="border-radius:var(--radius-lg); padding:clamp(24px,4vw,40px)">
        <h2>Where a claim isn't proven yet, we say so.</h2>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-inverse-muted); max-width:64ch">This is a pilot. None of the above is settled
          law or a ratified standard — it's the protocol's current, testable position. Where a claim isn't yet
          proven, we've said so in plain text rather than rounded it up. If your hardest question isn't here,
          send it — the gaps are the roadmap.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
